<br>
Think of it this way, Afghanistan was the first campaign in the War on Terror, simaltaneously we built up bases and assets to threaten other theatres in the war, propped up allied governments, engaged in operations intended to stretch the resources of the enemy, aided our allies in holding actions against our enemies (Israel vrs the Palestinian terrorists) and begun shaping the battlefield to our liking.  The preparation and planning are almost more important than the fighting itself, it is a truism for the military that amateurs discuss tactics, professionals discuss logistics, it is the invisible factors at work that make later military success inevitable.<br>
<br>
Small skirmishs and intel gathering in wartime are just as, if not more, important than the major battles that are studied in the history books.  The Battle of Gettysburg, arguably the turning point in the Civil War,  began as a small skirmish between a Union cavalry patrol and a Confederate foraging party, after all.  The little skirmishs and the intel leads to the major fights, and shapes the arena in which those major battles are fought.<br>
<br>
Now, it is certainly your right to be concerned by the actions of the government, civilian audit is vital to the proper functioning of a Western democracy and the American system of governance.  Even if I disagree with it, it would be stupid and assinine of me to dismiss it out of hand, because those concerns point up the failure of the Administration to properly inform the citizenry of what is going on, and, in my opinion, illustrates the sorry state of education in our society where the study of Military History is so sadly neglected in our schools that the majority of the populace doesn't understand these things.  If, after reviewing the historical antecedents and educating yourself as to the 'facts on the ground' as it were, you still disagree, then by all means do so, there is no 'one true conclusion' from history or anything else, reasonable, intelligent people can see the exact same pieces of data and form different opinions, and THAT is why consensual governance will always triumph over authoritarianism.  I might be wrong in my interpretation of what is going on, and you completely right, or the other way around, or some blend of the two.  In an authoritarian regime, once the 'truth' is defined by those in charge, to challenge it is death, in consensual governance, the illustration of folly can lead to its rectification. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uirexes.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Irexes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 90<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/16/02 5:24:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1218.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: War...</span><hr size=1> =======================================<br>
